==New York Mets broadcasters==
{{main|List of New York Mets broadcasters}}

===Television===
Most Mets games are carried by [[SportsNet New York]] (SNY), a joint venture of the Mets and [[NBC Sports Regional Networks]]. The team's terrestrial broadcast home is [[WPIX]], where the team has broadcast games since 1999.

Longtime Mets radio announcer [[Gary Cohen]] does the play-by-play, having moved to television with the launch of SNY in 2006. Former Mets [[Keith Hernandez]] and [[Ron Darling]] are the color commentators with [[Steve Gelbs]] being the on the field reporter.

In early January 2016, Keith Hernandez re-signed with SNY. Reports indicate that Hernandez received a raise and three-year contract.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title = Keith Hernandez to return to SNY|url = https://www.sny.tv/mets/news/keith-hernandez-to-return-to-sny/161798482|website = SNY|access-date = February 3, 2016}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Radio===
Beginning in 2019, Mets games are broadcast on [[WCBS (AM)|WCBS-AM 880]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation|title=WCBS 880 To Be Mets' New Flagship Radio Home |url=https://wfan.radio.com/articles/news/wcbs-880-be-mets-new-flagship-radio-home |work= |publisher=WFAN Sports Radio |author=Entercom Communications |date=September 17, 2018  |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Howie Rose]] is the main play-by-play announcer; [[Josh Lewin]], his broadcast partner since 2012, will not return.&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation|title=Wayne Randazzo Likely Headed to Mets' Radio Booth |url=https://sportsradiopd.com/wayne-randazzo-likely-headed-to-mets-radio-booth/ |work= |publisher=BSM Sports Media |author= |date=December 4, 2018  |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; Wayne Randazzo, who previously hosted the pre- and post-game shows, will replace Lewin; longtime Mets beat reporter [[Ed Coleman (radio personality)|Ed Coleman]] will take over the pre- and post-game role for most games.&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation|title=The new Mets booth will start on a short leash |url=https://nypost.com/2019/01/02/the-new-mets-booth-will-start-on-a-short-leash|work= |publisher=New York Post |author=Marchand, Andrew |date=January 2, 2019  |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The Mets' previous radio flagship was [[WOR (AM)|WOR-AM]],&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.wor710.com/articles/local-news-465659/the-mets-find-new-home-at-11791827/ The Mets Find New Home at WOR&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; from 2014-2018.&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation|title=New York Mets Move Radio Broadcasts To WCBS/Entercom |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/setheverett/2018/09/18/new-york-mets-move-radio-broadcasts-to-wcbs-entercom/#52e0556343c8/ |work= |publisher=Forbes |author=Everett, Seth |date=September 18, 2018  |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;  The Mets were previously carried by [[WFAN (AM)|WFAN-AM]], which inherited the team's broadcast rights from [[WEPN (AM)#WHN|WHN]] when it took over its frequency in 1987, and in later years by [[WFAN-FM]] which simulcasts the AM signal.

Spanish-language broadcasts are carried by [[WEPN (AM)|WEPN-AM 1050]], ESPN Deportes Nueva York, featuring Juan Alicea and Max Perez-Jimenez.&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation|title=Mets Radio &amp; TV Coverage |url=https://www.mlb.com/mets/team/broadcast-information |work= |publisher=New York Mets |author= |date=  |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Rose, who has spent much of his career covering the Mets, replaced [[Bob Murphy (broadcaster)|Bob Murphy]] as Gary Cohen's broadcast partner in 2004 following Murphy's retirement. Cohen then left the radio booth for the [[SportsNet New York|SNY]] television booth in 2006 and was replaced by [[Tom McCarthy (broadcaster)|Tom McCarthy]], who departed after two seasons and was replaced by [[Wayne Hagin]]. Lewin joined the broadcast after the team parted ways with Hagin following the 2011 season.

Coinciding with the move to WCBS, the Mets, abruptly and without public announcement (other than a brief e-mail to its affiliates days before the season began), stopped syndicating its games to other stations outside the New York City area, shutting down the [[New York Mets Radio Network]].&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.timesunion.com/sports/article/Mets-abandon-upstate-radio-network-for-2019-season-13727103.php Mets abandon upstate radio network for 2019 season] from the ''Times-Union'' of Albany, NY; April 1, 2019&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.syracuse.com/mets/2019/04/new-york-mets-radio-blackout-a-middle-finger-to-cny-fans-ceo-says.html New York Mets radio blackout a ‘middle finger’ to CNY fans, CEO says], from The Post-Standard of Syracuse, NY (April 1, 2019)&lt;/ref&gt;

